WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hi everyone, we're here at Data Plus AI Summit and look who I have with me, Eric, the SVP of Product and Strategy at Posit.

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Eric, welcome to the Ravit Show, such a pleasure to host you today.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:15.000
I'm excited to learn a little about what's happening at Posit, also a little about your role,

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
and I know you all have a deeper partnership with Databricks as well, so wanting to learn a little about that.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:29.000
But why not, just for our audience, quickly tell us a little about yourself, what do you do at Posit, and also a little about Posit too, please.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Well, thank you, thank you for having me, it's a pleasure to be with you today.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
My name is Eric Pité, I've been with the company for about five and a half years.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:47.000
I lead Product and Strategy, so product management, strategic integration partnership like Databricks, where we are today.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Fantastic.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:50.000
And yeah, that's me in a nutshell.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Fantastic, Eric, thanks for sharing that.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:00.000
I've seen Posit for a while now, but I also followed RStudio back then.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:06.000
So I'm kind of wanting to know a little bit about that story too, about Posit's rebrand from RStudio,

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:14.000
and also a little bit if you can talk about the increased focus on Python.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Yeah, for sure.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:16.000
Can you share a little bit?

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Yeah, so the company was created under the name RStudio about 16 years ago by JJ Allaire,

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.000
and he decided to give back to the community by building better tooling for the R ecosystem.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Right.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:41.000
After that, Joe Chang also built Shiny, and Hadley Wickham built many open source R packages over the years.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And about seven, eight years ago, we realized that R is really important, but for data science, Python is equally important.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Yep.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
So we started to make investments in a Python ecosystem.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Nice.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:00.000
And we realized that the name, the brand RStudio was working against us.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:07.000
The analogy we often take is if you have a friend who's vegan, you want to take your friend to a restaurant and it says a steakhouse.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Yeah.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.000
You're going to have a hard time to explain to your friend.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:20.000
So about three years ago almost now, we decided to rebrand from RStudio to Posit so that we are not tied to one language.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.000
We are building a company that we hope is going to be around for over 100 years.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Yep.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And so 100 years, there won't be R, there won't be Python, so being tied to a language name was a challenge.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:32.000
So that's why we rebranded.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
But it's the same company.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:39.000
It's the same company, but now I get the analogy behind changing the name.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:40.000
So that's fantastic.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Thanks for sharing that.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:51.000
Also talking a little bit about, you know, since you all started open source, how do you kind of keep that balance between open source and the enterprise?

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
But at the same time, Posit balances between machine, community, and commercials.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Yeah.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:05.000
So that's a massive way to balance things and at the same time give back to the community as much as possible.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Yeah, that's true.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Can you tell a little about that?

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:08.000
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
So the company was really founded initially to build great open source products.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Right.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And we built what we call the virtual circle, which we create great open source products that get traction in the market.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Those data scientists using it will then go into enterprise, want to use those tools, and we build enterprise-grade solution, leveraging this open source solution.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.000
We charge for that.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.000
And then the proceed that we get, we reinvest back in the open source.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So that's kind of this virtual circle.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Right.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:50.000
So we have, you know, between 1,700 and 1,800 customers.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.000
Wow.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And each time I meet them, I say, you know, whether you know it or not, you actually contribute to open source.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Exactly.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:58.000
That's so true.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Because about 40% of our engineering is dedicated to open source that we give away.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.000
So the root of the company is really open source.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:14.000
About five and a half years ago, six years ago, we moved the company from a C corporation to a public benefit corporation.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Nice.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:19.000
So maybe some of your listeners don't know quite what a public benefit corporation is.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:23.000
So when you're a C corporation, you have one goal, maximization of shareholder value.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:24.000
This is it.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Yeah.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
So for public benefit corporation, there are multiple stakeholders.

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:32.000
And we basically inscribe that in our charter.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:37.000
You know, customers, employees, the greater good that we specify in our charter.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
Right.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
So we made that change about five and a half years ago.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.000
That's fantastic.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Yeah.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
It's for the greater good and for the community as well.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So those are fantastic insights, Eric.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Thanks for sharing that.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:59.000
I kind of also have like a little bit of curiosity around Positron and the Posit Databricks partnership.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
Since you look after the integration bit as well, can you share a little about that?

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:04.000
Yeah.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So I'll start with Databricks since we are hosted by Databricks here today.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
We integrate our products with them so that there is no headache for the end user.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:19.000
You know, they don't need to have, you know, specific access token to access.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Everything is integrated inside POSIX Workbench to make their life easy.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.000
So, you know, all the credential pass through.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:37.000
And what we do, which is really important also, is like make sure that we leverage all the data governance that Databricks offers that is very strong.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:44.000
So if we build an interactive application, you know, you access it, I access it.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:46.000
We have different access within Databricks.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:47.000
We would see different things.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:48.000
Yeah.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:54.000
So, you know, inheriting the governance that you have in Databricks, I think is really important for enterprise.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
We do it for Databricks.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:58.000
In all transparency, we do it for others as well.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
You know, Snowflake and other players.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Yeah.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
So that's for the Databricks side.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Positron, you know, so we started as RStudio.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.000
The RStudio idea was the first product we built.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And we've learned a lot over more than 10 years.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And we had a lot of customers and users coming to us and say, could you do PyStudio?

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.000
You know, basically RStudio for the Python language.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:24.000
Yeah.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And so a few years ago, we decided to solve this problem, which is offer a multi-language ID specifically for data scientists.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
So we took a fork out of VS Code.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Right.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:44.000
Leveraging all the great ecosystem and all the extension you can get from VS Code.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.000
But really focusing on solving the problems that data scientists have.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So all the good learnings over the last 10 plus years on the RStudio ID are now in Positron, which is available to date for download.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
And we'll go GA next month.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.000
That's awesome.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
So we'll wait for that.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
Thank you for sharing that on the Robert show.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.000
We're excited to see how that's kind of coming together.

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:13.000
I'm kind of also wanting to learn a little bit about Posit's view on AI for data science.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:14.000
Yeah.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
That is something huge because everyone's kind of, you know, obviously we've been hearing the buzz around AI.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
We've been seeing fantastic use cases coming around AI.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
But how does it look like in data science?

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.000
That's a great question.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
AI is all the buzz these days.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.000
Everywhere you go.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Right.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:38.000
The pace of improvement has been hard to believe for me.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:43.000
If anyone told me three years ago I'd be able to do what I'm able to do today, I probably wouldn't have believed it.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
No way. Yeah, exactly.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.000
So we want to empower, you know, data scientists to do more.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:54.000
And we have a number of products integrated in Positron to be able to do that.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:55.000
Nice.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:59.000
From code assistant to doing exploratory data analysis.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
But we want to do it in a very responsible way.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:08.000
We realize that, you know, there's a lot of trust given into a data scientist.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:14.000
So our data scientists need to be able to see and prove what they're doing.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:18.000
We know that LLMs are prone to hallucination.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:24.000
So that's kind of our take, which is, you know, really empower the data scientists in a very responsible way.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:29.000
By showing them the code, letting them edit and inspect the code.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:30.000
I love it.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:36.000
So that's definitely super helpful for, you know, the users.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
But also leveraging AI in the best way possible.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:39.000
Yes.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:40.000
So that's fantastic, Eric.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.000
One more quick question I had was around the communication bit.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.000
So communicating data-driven work with code and storytelling.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
Why do you think it's important?

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:51.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:57.000
So, you know, if you look at the flow of a data scientist, you know, usually you want to answer a question or multiple questions.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
You access data, you write code.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.000
We're a code-first company.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Yes.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
You write code to generate your insight.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.000
You're very happy with yourself, but then you need to share that with other stakeholders, right?

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
You're not going to go with your laptop around the office to share that.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:16.000
So we've built a number of products.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
Some of them are free and open source.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
Others are more for the enterprise.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And so they're coupled.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:29.000
Exposite Connect really allows the data scientist to publish a lot of artifacts.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Right.

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And about three, four years ago, we built something called Quarto.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:45.000
So Quarto helps you do what we call literate programming, which I think was coined by probably Donald Knuth many years ago.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:53.000
Ten plus years ago, we did R Markdown, which allows you to have code and prose and all of that in the same document.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
So we revamped that to be, again, multilingual.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:57.000
You could do it with the R language.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
You could do it with Python.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:00.000
You could do it with Julia.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
You could do it with Observable, JS, if you want, and many other things.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
And that's also a testimony to balancing for us, you know, open source versus enterprise solution.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:15.000
We believe that products like Quarto should be accessible and available to everybody.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:16.000
Right.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:17.000
And that's why it's fully open source for us.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:20.000
That's very important and very thoughtful as well.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.000
So thanks for making sure that Posit is for the community.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:29.000
As always, the machine never stops to give it back to the community.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:36.000
But at the same time, you all have, like, fine balance between the commercial side and, you know, the enterprise side as well, which is fantastic.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Eric, one last question for our audience.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:47.000
If folks want to stay updated with all the insights, all the announcements, everything that you all are producing, where can they do that?

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:51.000
And also, if they want to follow you, where can they follow you?

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:52.000
Is LinkedIn a best place?

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
LinkedIn is a good place, probably the best place for me.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:59.000
But more important for the company, you know, our website, we have newsletter.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:03.000
We have a strong presence on LinkedIn, Blue Sky.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Nice.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.000
But I would invite everybody to follow us on LinkedIn and subscribe to the newsletters.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.000
Fantastic.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:16.000
So you all know where you can follow Posit and team and stay updated with all the insights.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
Eric, such a pleasure chatting with you.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Likewise.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:20.000
We'll keep the conversation going.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
Great work that you all are doing in this space.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:23.000
Thank you very much.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.000
Appreciate it.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:25.000
Thank you.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Thank you, everyone, for joining us today.

